%N A247975 Least positive integer m such that m + n divides prime(m)^2 + prime(n)^2.
%C A247975 Conjecture: a(n) exists for any n > 0. - _Zhi-Wei Sun_, Sep 28 2014
%C A247975 If a(i) = j, then a(j) <= i. - _Derek Orr_, Sep 28 2014
%C A247975 Computational extension to n = 1..100000 (search bound a(n) <= 1.6*10^10; i.e., p_{a(n)} <= 3.72*10^11): 13 values remain unresolved within this bound (n = 22802, 23995, 37249, 37253, 37949, 43297, 48834, 53963, 66257, 69546, 76868, 82300, 98379), all with estimated ratio a(n)/(n*log(n)) > 14000. The global maximum ratio among resolved cases is at n = 11924 (ratio approximately 54679, new record), with a(11924) = 6119832581; the previous record was n = 4703 (ratio approximately 19111). - _Carlo Corti_, Mar 11 2026
%H A247975 Chai Wah Wu, <a href="/A247975/b247975.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a> (n = 1..5000 from Zhi-Wei Sun)
%H A247975 Carlo Corti, <a href="/A247975/a247975.txt">Extended dataset: a(n) for n = 1..100000 (99987 resolved values, 13 gaps)</a>
%H A247975 Carlo Corti, <a href="https://github.com/carcorti/A247975">Code and data repository for the computational study of A247975</a>, GitHub, 2026.
